Alphabet Soup¶

A problem of decrypting encrypted words using Python | By Sian Thompson¶

Here's the Alphabet Soup problem:¶

A list contains 10 common English words. However, they are incomplete. Zeros in each word represent where letters of the alphabet should substitute these. There are at least 26 zeros and each letter of the alphabet should be used exactly once to substitute the zeros and arrive at decrypted words.

The answers should be provided in a dictionary where encrypted words correspond to decrypted words.

Here's the encrypted list of words:

encrypted_words = ['0ri0t', '0ala00', '0e00est', '0e00ry', '0ra0e0', 's00r0', '00amy', '0ebr0', '0o0ey','0ro0ec0']

Here's the desired outcome as a dictionary:

answers_dict = {'0ri0t':'wrist', '0ala00': 'galaxy', '0e00est':'request', '0e00ry': 'celery',\'0ra0e0': 'braved', 's00r0':'shirk', '00amy':'foamy', '0ebr0': 'zebra', '0o0ey': 'money', '0ro0ec0': 'project'}

Now, I would like to point out, this challenge is not as simple as it looks. Please note the above python word challenge has taken inspiration from the following guardian article:

https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jul/13/can-you-solve-it-alphabet-soup

Approaching the problem¶

An obvious issue with this problem is that if you substitute zeros to derive a 'test word', you would need to check whether the word is a potential English word which can be used. Also, producing a list of test words with all possible combinations with letters from the alphabet could take a long time if we were to consider a 'brute force' method.

Thus, I thought about how I can optimise fetching the most potential words for an encrypted word, based on varying the number of test words. Ultimately, I took on an approach that passes a test word to a NLP (Natural Language Processing) object and spellchecks the word to derive proxy words. In this process, the proxy words have to be checked to see whether are truly a potential word for the encrypted word.

Using NLP libaries for spellchecking test words¶

I researched the following Python spellchecking libraries, which came with various strengths and weaknesses with regard to solving the problem:

TextBlob

  • TextBlob is similar to the NLP Spacy library in that you can pass text such as a sentence to a NLP object in order to tag words e.g. as nouns etc.
  • It references standing 'on the giant shoulders of NLTK and pattern'.
  • What I discovered was that Textblob seemed to be more suitable than Spacy in evaluating individual words.

Pyspellchecker

  • Pyspellchecker provides some sophisticated spellschecking functionality.

Creating code to find proxy words using TextBlob and Pyspellchecker¶

  • In this section, we will evaluate the selection of proxy words derived from using the spellchecking libraries upon the encrypted and and decrypted words provided in the answers_dict dictionary.
from spellchecker import SpellChecker # Pyspellchecker
from textblob import Word as Textblob #Textblob
import pandas as pd

answers_dict = {'0ri0t':'wrist', '0ala00': 'galaxy', '0e00est':'request', '0e00ry': 'celery',
                '0ra0e0': 'braved', 's00r0':'shirk', '00amy':'foamy', '0ebr0': 'zebra', 
                '0o0ey': 'money', '0ro0ec0': 'project'}

spell_checker = SpellChecker() #Pyspellchecker instance only has to be instantiated once 

def get_text_blob_proxy_words(test_word):
    """
    Note the Textblob object has to be reinstantiated everytime you want 
    to spellcheck a test word. Also textblob_proxy_words provides a list of tuples,
    e.g. [(foam, 0.8), (foams, 0.2)] for the test word foamy.
    Numbers provide a weighting of what a word may potentially be in a spellchecking 
    scenario, rather than in this decryption scenario where we need to be mindful of 
    the encrypyted word length. Thus the list comprehension below extracts the proxy 
    words. Words with a weighting of 0 do not count as words and can be ignored. This 
    particularly applies to the encrypted words which are returned in no proxy words 
    are found e.g. [(s00r0, 0.0)] 
    """
    textblob = Textblob(test_word)
    textblob_proxy_words = textblob.spellcheck()
    #return textblob_proxy_words
    return [k for k,v in textblob_proxy_words if v >0 ]


column_indexes = [v for v in answers_dict.values()] + [k for k in answers_dict.keys()]
pyspellchecker_proxy_words = [list(spell_checker.candidates(x)) for x in column_indexes]
# Note spell_checker.candidates(x) set is cast as a list for consistency

text_blob_proxy_words = [get_text_blob_proxy_words(x) for x in column_indexes]

Evaluation of results from dataframe¶

Typically, both spellcheckers seem to return fewer words if there are more zeros present in the encrypted words.

Textblob

  • The feature of providing weightings means that non-words can easily be excluded if they return 0 as explained within the function 'get_text_blob_proxy_words' above. In such cases, an empty list has been returned, particularly for encrypted words which include zeros.
  • Looking at the decrypted words 'celery', 'foamy' and 'zebra', it would seem the Textblob corpus is incomplete as these words are not respectfully returned.

Pyspellchecker

  • If there is only one result in the list, it would be necessary to check whether the proxy word contains zeros, so that non-words can be excluded.
  • Seems to provide more proxy words, particularly for the encrypted words which is highly advantageous.
  • However, testing other test words, this can be beyond the English language and can thus introduce noise.
  • Ultimately, this means that there would be more potential words available for each letter of the alphabet, which may further distance ourselves from solving the problem

It's important to note that proxy words can only be considered as potential words if they are:

a) the same length of the encrypted word and b) retain the same letters at index positions which are not zero.

Considerations in GitHub project¶

All these points have been considered for creating classes that find potential words, based on proxy words delivered from using the spellchecking libaries. These can be found here:

  • TextBlobWordFinder
  • PyspellcheckerWordFinder

Within my GitHub project, word finder classes based on each of the spellchecking libaries, spellcheck test words, beyond the encrypted word passed to the instance. Test words are generated by substituting random letters at index positions for the zeros in the encrypyted word.

The TextBlobWordFinder bypasses spellchecking the encrypted words directly, compared to the PyspellcheckerWordFinder in my project. However, as a consequence, there is a epoching process which takes time to accumulate a minimum number of required potential words. There are various parameters defined by the user. By contrast, the PyspellcheckerWordFinder only spellchecks a limited number of test words, because it is effective in obtaining proxy words directly from some of the encrypted words.

Building a Dictionary of Encrypted words with Potential words¶

With regard to each encrypted word, a dictionary is built with a list of potential words. This also includes a list of indexes for where zeros occur in the original encrypted word. Dictionaries for each encrypted word become nested within a a larger dictionary. This is referred to as a potential_word_dict_collection in my GitHub project. This example is built from using the TextBlobWordFinder:

{'0ri0t': {'potential_words_list': ['print', 'grist', 'wrist', 'drift'], 'zeros_list': [0, 3], 'success': True},
'0ala00': {'potential_words_list': ['malady', 'balaga', 'galant', 'galaxy', 'falaba', 'palate', 'salary', 'palace'], 'zeros_list': [0, 4, 5], 'success': True}...
'0ebr0': {'potential_words_list': [], 'zeros_list': [0, 4], 'success': False},
'0ro0ec0': {'potential_words_list': ['project', 'protect'], 'zeros_list': [0, 3, 6], 'success': True}}

Building a Dictionary whereby Encrypted words are assigned to the alphabetical letters¶

The PotentialWordTracker helps build a potential_words_by_alpha_dict object which stores key words pairs for potential words and encrypted words by alphabetical order. As this is a large object to display, only a sample is provided below:

{'a': {'balaga': '0ala00', 'falaba': '0ala00', 'meanest': '0e00est', 'dearest': '0e00est', ...},
'b': {'balaga': '0ala00', 'falaba': '0ala00', 'bequest': '0e00est', 'belfry': '0e00ry'...},
'c': {'palace': '0ala00', 'descry': '0e00ry', 'traced': '0ra0e0', 'traces': '0ra0e0', ...}...
'z': {'grazed': '0ra0e0', 'brazen': '0ra0e0'} }

Assigning Potential words to Encrypted words using a decoder¶

Assigning potential words to encrypted words demands a process of assignment. Considering the dictionary above, the EncryptedWordDecoder can be run to build a collection of decrypted word dictionaries. This is built over a series of epochs due to randomisation effects in the algorithm.

Remember, the final objective is to find optimal user-defined parameters, whereby as many 'correct' potential words can be assigned to the encrypted words, as per the answers_dict as possible.

In each decrypted word dictionary, a single potential word is assigned to each of the 10 encrypted words. Here's an example of a decrypted word dictionary:

{'00amy': 'liamy','0ala00': 'galaxy','0e00est': 'request','0e00ry': 'kefcry', '0ebr0': 'sebro','0o0ey': 'dovey','0ra0e0': 'brazen','0ri0t': 'hriet','0ro0ec0': 'project', 's00r0': 'swarm'}

Here's an overview of the process of assignment in a single epoch:

  1. Get the starting letters: This is a list of letters where only one potential word has been assigned to a letter in the potential_words_by_alpha_dict parameter. If there are fewer than two starting letters, two random letters are chosen for this.
  2. Usually, for each starting letter, a decrypted word dictionary is built where the single corresponding key value pair is the first to be assigned to the decrypted word dictionary. e.g. 'g' might only have { 'galaxy': '0ala00'}.
  3. Progressively, letters are removed from a copy of the potential_words_by_alpha_dict as they may be included at zero index positions of the encrypted word which is added to the decrypted word dictionary. Nested pairs of encrypted word along with potential words are also removed.
  4. The algorithm progressively assigns further encrypted words to the decrypted word dictionary, by prioritising those with the fewest key value pairs available in the potential_words_by_alpha_dict. This can involve some random selection.
  5. The final stage finally randomly assigns unassigned letters to unassigned words. Not the perfect solution, but as highlighted above the spellcheckers are not perfect at identifying true words.

Evaluating results from changing user-defined parameters¶

The Experimenter in my project executes two distinct methods which correspond to using the word finder classes to obtain proxy words as separate prerequisites to running the EncryptedWordDecoder. Parameters which can be tweaked for each of these are listed for each respective method below.

  • get_results_for_text_blob_word_finder
    • max_epochs: Maximum no. of epochs which are run with a minimum number of interations
    • min_iters_per_epoch: Minimum no. of iterations in an epoch. In each iteration, letters randomly substitute the zeros in the word to produce a test word.
    • min_potential_words: If the threshold of providing a minimum number of potential words is not satisfied following epoching, then another attempt is made to derive proxy words for the encrypted words.
    • max_attempts: Limits the number of attempts for epoching
  • get_results_for_pyspellchecker_word_finder
    • pyspellchecker_no_of_random_letters: Should be in between 1 and 27. Represents no. of random letters which would be substituted into encrypted words at the first zero index position to produce test words

There is also a parameter which sets the maximum number of epochs which are run for the decoder.

The Experimenter can be run by executing the src.main.py script. This assigns different values to each of the parameters above as part of stress tests. It integrates a ReportMaker which helps output parameters with results in a csv report: which can be downloaded here:

alphabet_soup_report.csv

The report has been produced by executing section 1 of the main script three times.

The results can be viewed in a pandas dataframe. Please note the no_of_runs corresponds to the number of decrypted word dictionaries that were collected in a stress test. This is typically twice the number of the maximum number of epochs run for the word decoder:

results_df = pd.read_csv("reports/alphabet_soup_report_fixed.csv")

Summary of Project¶

Overall, accuracy measures are not entirely dependent on the word finders. However, their role is key to finding potential words for encrypted words. The EncryptedWordDecoder introduces further randomness in the way in which words may be assigned to encrypted words. As one idea, the algorithm could be improved to spell check words when unassigned letters are assigned to unassigned words. Whilst this may prolong the time that the algorithm takes to run, greater mean accuracy could be expected. But, it's important to note the success rate of this would be determined by the scope of the spellchecker corpus and capabilities as has been discussed. Thus, further research could take place into alternative spellcheckers.

Next steps for this project could be to train a machine learning algorithm to find decrypted words based on encrypted words. This project only considered one use case, presented in the answers_dict, but a training set could be developed with further words to decrypt. This shouldn't overlook that each zero can only be substituted once by each respective letter of the alphabet in each use case.

Thanks for reading! If you made it this far, hat off to you :)
